Subsequent conversion to Ag2X2(MeOCH2CH2ImCH2CH2ImMe) (X = Cl (3a), Br (3b)) was achieved by treatment with Ag2O. Reaction of 3a or 3b with RuCl2(PPh3)3 (4) afforded RuCl2(PPh3)­(MeOCH2CH2ImCH2CH2ImMe) (5). In a similar fashion treatment of 3a or 3b with RuCl2(CHPh)­(PCy3)2 gave the alkylidene complex RuCl2(CHPh)­(MeOCH2CH2ImCH2CH2ImMe) (6). In several standard metathesis tests 6 was shown to be a poor catalyst. The related ligand precursor [O­(CH2CH2ImMe)2]­[Br]2 (7) was prepared, transformed to (AgBr)2[O­(CH2CH2ImMe)2] (8) and reacted with RuCl2(CHPh)­(PCy3)2 to give RuCl2(CHPh)­[O­(CH2CH2ImMe)2] (9). Structural data for 3a, 5, 6, 9, and 10 are reported, and the implications of this work in catalyst development are considered.

elements.content: Olefin metathesis has become a widespread synthetic tool for altering the chemical composition of organic substrates and has been successfully utilized in disciplines such as natural product, polymer, pharmaceutical, and industrial chemistry. Catalysts most often chosen for these transformations include the Grubbs first-generation precatalyst RuCl2(CHPh)­(PCy3)2 (1) and second-generation precatalyst RuCl2(CHPh)­(PCy3)­(SIMes) (Figure ) or alternatively the variations known as the Grubbs–Hoveyda precatalysts, which incorporate alkylidenes with the pendant ether groups (Figure ). Additional alterations to the first- and second-generation Grubbs catalysts have been developed, as substitution of the phosphine with other monodentate ligands such as amines and carbenes reduces the initiation times, increases stability and activity, and improves selectivity. A significant number of ruthenium olefin metathesis catalysts have been prepared that feature bidentate ligands. In some cases, the catalysts displayed improved selectivity, thermal stability, tunability, and tolerance to protic media in comparison to the case for monodentate analogues. Ru alkylidene species which incorporate tridentate ligands are also known; however, these catalysts seem to result in lower activity in exchange for higher stability. Herein, we report the synthesis of new tridentate ligand complexes of Ru. Strategies targeting reactive metathesis catalysts involving the incorporation of one weak donor group or halide abstraction are investigated. The implications of these data for the design of new metathesis catalysts are considered.

X-ray Data Collection, Reduction, Solution, and Refinement

Single crystals were mounted in thin-walled capillaries either under an atmosphere of dry N2 in a glovebox and flame-sealed or coated in Paratone-N oil. The data were collected using the SMART software package on a Siemens SMART System CCD diffractometer using a graphite monochromator with Mo Kα radiation (λ = 0.71073 Å). Data reduction was performed using the SAINT software package and an absorption correction applied using SADABS. The structures were solved by direct methods using XS and refined by full-matrix least squares on F 2 using XL as implemented in the SHELXTL suite of programs. All non-hydrogen atoms were refined anisotropically. Carbon-bound hydrogen atoms were placed in calculated positions using an appropriate riding model and coupled isotropic temperature factors.

elements.content: We envisioned tridentate ligands that featured two N-heterocyclic carbenes tethered together with a short aliphatic chain and one weakly binding donor. The inspiration for such ligands was in part due to the enhanced stability and activity of the Grubbs second-generation catalyst resulting from replacement of PCy3 with an NHC. We further speculated that a meridionally bound ligand would allow for the coordination of a weak donor cis to the alkylidene fragment, a feature thought to facilitate an active catalyst. Finally, we chose an ether group as the weak donor, as this fragment is both easily incorporated into the ligand framework and known to afford weak Ru–O bonds. With these concepts in mind, the ligand precursors [MeOCH2CH2ImCH2CH2ImMe]­X2 (X = Cl (2a), Br (2b)) were readily prepared by refluxing an equimolar mixture of methoxyethylimidazole with a haloethylmethylimidazolium halide in acetonitrile. The resulting white solids 2a,b were isolated in high yields (Scheme ). The 1H NMR spectra for 2a,b revealed the characteristic imidazolium resonances for the NCHN groups at 9.55 and 9.60 ppm for 2a and 9.20 and 9.22 ppm for 2b. The associated NCHN 13C NMR resonances were located at 137.14 and 137.39 ppm for 2a and 136.86 and 137.11 ppm for 2b.

Results and Discussion

CCO-bis(carbene) Ligand Complexes

We envisioned tridentate ligands that featured two N-heterocyclic carbenes tethered together with a short aliphatic chain and one weakly binding donor. The inspiration for such ligands was in part due to the enhanced stability and activity of the Grubbs second-generation catalyst resulting from replacement of PCy3 with an NHC. We further speculated that a meridionally bound ligand would allow for the coordination of a weak donor cis to the alkylidene fragment, a feature thought to facilitate an active catalyst. Finally, we chose an ether group as the weak donor, as this fragment is both easily incorporated into the ligand framework and known to afford weak Ru-O bonds. With these concepts in mind, the ligand precursors [MeOCH2CH2ImCH2CH2ImMe]X2 (X = Cl (2a), Br (2b)) were readily prepared by refluxing an equimolar mixture of methoxyethylimidazole with a haloethylmethylimidazolium halide in acetonitrile. The resulting white solids 2a,b were isolated in high yields (Scheme ). The 1H NMR spectra for 2a,b revealed the characteristic imidazolium resonances for the NCHN groups at 9.55 and 9.60 ppm for 2a and 9.20 and 9.22 ppm for 2b. The associated NCHN 13C NMR resonances were located at 137.14 and 137.39 ppm for 2a and 136.86 and 137.11 ppm for 2b.

To assess the viability of 3a,b as a transmetalating agent, a slurry of either of these species in CH2Cl2 was treated with a solution of RuCl2(PPh3)3 (4), yielding an orange solution containing 5 in either case (Scheme ). The 1H NMR spectra of 5 revealed a 31P NMR singlet at 58.93 ppm indicating a single phosphine environment. The 13C NMR spectra also suggested that transmetalation was successful, as the ipso carbons for the N-heterocyclic carbenes were now located at 180.32 ppm, although this could only be observed in HMBC (heteronuclear multiple bond correlation) spectra. Single crystals of 5 were obtained from a tetrahydrofuran/diethyl ether mixture, and the structure of 5 was shown to be RuCl2(PPh3)­(MeOCH2CH2ImCH2CH2ImMe) (Figure ). In this species the Ru center adopts a pseudo-octahedral environment with the tridentate ligand bound in a meridional fashion with the central NHC fragment trans to chloride, while the terminal NHC was trans to the Ru–O bond of the coordinated ether. This latter carbene gave rise to a Ru–C bond length of 1.984(8) Å, which is shorter than the Ru–C bond length of 2.044(9) Å for the central NHC fragment. These differences are consistent with the weaker trans influence of ether in comparison to that of chloride. The corresponding Ru–Cl and Ru–O bond lengths are 2.483(2) and 2.295(6) Å. The latter is elongated in comparison to the sum of the covalent radii (1.99 Å), an indication of the potential lability of this ethereal fragment. The coordination is completed with trans-disposed Ru–P and Ru–Cl bonds of 2.298(2) and 2.485(2) Å.

elements.content: The utility of 6 as a metathesis catalyst was assessed employing standard metathesis tests including ring-closing metathesis (RCM) of diethyl diallylmalonate, the ring-opening metathesis polymerization (ROMP) of 1,5-cyclooctadiene, and the cross-metathesis (CM) of 5-hexenyl acetate with methyl acrylate. Species 6 is a poor catalyst for all of these transformations at 45 °C in CD2Cl2 and at 80 °C in DMSO-d 6 (Tables – ). Indeed, the best result obtained was for the RCM reaction, where 24% conversion to product was observed after 72 h. Nonetheless, in all cases 6 was observed spectroscopically on following the reaction, suggesting that the six-coordinate nature of 6 precludes initiation.

The 1H NMR spectrum was indicative of a clean transformation to a new alkylidene-containing species with a CH shift of 19.93 ppm. The 11B NMR shift at −6.97 ppm and corresponding 19F NMR signals were consistent with the generation of the anion [ClB­(C6F5)3]−. These data suggest the formulation of 10 as [RuCl­(CHPh)­[O­(CH2CH2ImMe)2]­[ClB­(C6F5)3]; however, dark blue crystals of 10 were isolated and crystallographically characterized (Figure ). The tridentate ligand on each Ru adopts a facial arrangement with the central oxygen donor being trans to the alkylidene on each Ru. The shortest contact between the counteranions [ClB­(C6F5)3]− and the dication is a Ru–F interspatial distance of 4.830 Å. The Ru–C distances for the alkylidene and the NHC ligands were found to be 1.850(3), 2.010(3), and 2.049(3) Å, respectively, which are similar to those seen in 9. The largest structural changes observed in the transformation of 9 to 10 is the marked shortening of the Ru–O bonds from 2.338(4) Å in 9 to 2.267(2) Å in 10, while as a result of the bridging positions, the Ru–Cl bonds are elongated to 2.5336(6) and 2.5631(7) Å.

In the case of 9 this species, although stable to the conditions, was shown to be effectively unreactive (Tables –). In contrast, 10 proved to be an active metathesis catalyst at 45 °C in RCM, ROMP, and CM test reactions, affording to corresponding products in conversions of 38, 50, and 15% after 24 h and 54, 55, and 18% after 72 h, respectively. At 80 °C, compound 10 showed elevated activity, giving 83% yield in the RCM test after 24 h. Although this catalyst is slow, it remains remarkably stable at 80 °C (Figure ). For example, the ring-closing metathesis of diethyl diallylmalonate took 96 h to reach completion, while the ROMP of COD gave a final conversion of 91% after 1 week of activity. The activity of 10 in metathesis suggests that the active species is likely the monometallic five-coordinate cationic Ru alkylidene.

Conclusions

Herein we have developed the synthesis of Ru complexes with tridentate bis(carbene) ether ligands. These ligands have been shown to adopt both facial and meridional coordination geometries. Despite the fact that the ether oxygen is a weak donor and occupies positions cis or trans to the alkylidene fragment in the neutral Ru alkylidene complexes 6 and 9, respectively, these species exhibit low, if any, activity in metathesis. Abstraction of halide results in better catalytic activity for the corresponding cationic alkylidene complex 10. As these ligands do provide greater stability to these alkylidene species, we are continuing to explore ligand variations with a view to uncovering systems with good stability but with enhanced reactivity properties.
